         <abstract>
            <p>Corporate financial policies on dividends, stock repurchases, and equity issues have long been a source of disagreement between academics and financial practitioners. This paper reports on recent empirical work that measures the capital market's reaction to equity cash flow decisions. That work suggests that all three corporate financial policies are related. It is also consistent with the view that financial decisions that affect equity cash flows are interpreted by outside investors as "signals" reflecting the inside management's appraisal of the firm's future cash flows.</p>
         </abstract>
